{"title":"PostgreSQL Setup","markdown":{"yaml":{"description":"postgreSQL","output-file":"postgresql_setup.html","skip_exec":true,"skip_showdoc":true,"title":"PostgreSQL Setup"},"headingText":"Install PostgreSQL","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n\n\n\n<!-- WARNING: THIS FILE WAS AUTOGENERATED! DO NOT EDIT! -->\n\n\n### Update\n> Update the package list before installing PostgreSQL\n\n```sh\nsudo apt-get update\n```\n\n### Install PostgreSQL\n> Install PostgreSQL and its client packages:\n\n```sh\nsudo apt-get install postgresql postgresql-contrib\n\n```\n\n### Verify Installation\n> Check the PostgreSQL version to verify installation:\n\n```sh\npsql --version\n```\n\n## Initialize and Configure PostgreSQL\n\n### Initialize PostgreSQL Cluster:\n> PostgreSQL installation typically initializes a cluster automatically. If not, you can do it manually:\n\n```sh\nsudo pg_createcluster 13 main --start\n\n```\n\n### Start PostgreSQL Service:\n\n```sh\nsudo service postgresql start\n```\n\n### Configure PostgreSQL User and Password\n> By default, PostgreSQL creates a user postgres with no password. Set a password for the postgres user if needed:\n\n```sh\nsudo -u postgres psql\n\\password postgres\n\\q\n\n```\n\n## Access PostgreSQL\n\n### Access PostgreSQL Shell (psql):\n\n```sh\nsudo -u postgres psql\n```\n\n### Basic Commands\n> Once in psql, you can execute SQL commands. Here are a few essential commands:\n\n- \\l: List all databases.\n- \\c database_name: Connect to a specific database.\n- \\dt: List all tables in the current database.\n- \\q: Quit psql.\n\n## Configure PostgreSQL for Use with Applications\n\n### Edit PostgreSQL Configuration (if necessary):\n\n> Modify PostgreSQL configuration files (postgresql.conf and pg_hba.conf) located typically in /etc/postgresql/<version>/main/ to adjust settings like authentication methods, listen addresses, etc.\n\n### Connect PostgreSQL with Django or Other Applications\n> Update your application's database settings (settings.py for Django) to use PostgreSQL with the appropriate credentials (USER, PASSWORD, HOST, PORT).\n\n## Remove PostgreSQL\n\n### Stop\n> If PostgreSQL is running, stop the service:\n\n```sh\nsudo service postgresql stop\n```\n\n### Remove\n> Remove PostgreSQL and its configuration files:\n```sh\nsudo apt-get remove --purge postgresql\\*\n```\n\n### Clean up\n> Remove any remaining configuration files:\n\n```sh\nsudo rm -r /etc/postgresql/\nsudo rm -r /etc/postgresql-common/\nsudo rm -r /var/lib/postgresql/\n\n\n\n```\n\n### Additional Tips\n\n- Backup and Restore: Use tools like pg_dump and pg_restore for database backups and restoration.\n- Security: Ensure PostgreSQL is configured securely, especially if accessible from outside WSL.\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n\n\n\n<!-- WARNING: THIS FILE WAS AUTOGENERATED! DO NOT EDIT! -->\n\n## Install PostgreSQL\n\n### Update\n> Update the package list before installing PostgreSQL\n\n```sh\nsudo apt-get update\n```\n\n### Install PostgreSQL\n> Install PostgreSQL and its client packages:\n\n```sh\nsudo apt-get install postgresql postgresql-contrib\n\n```\n\n### Verify Installation\n> Check the PostgreSQL version to verify installation:\n\n```sh\npsql --version\n```\n\n## Initialize and Configure PostgreSQL\n\n### Initialize PostgreSQL Cluster:\n> PostgreSQL installation typically initializes a cluster automatically. If not, you can do it manually:\n\n```sh\nsudo pg_createcluster 13 main --start\n\n```\n\n### Start PostgreSQL Service:\n\n```sh\nsudo service postgresql start\n```\n\n### Configure PostgreSQL User and Password\n> By default, PostgreSQL creates a user postgres with no password. Set a password for the postgres user if needed:\n\n```sh\nsudo -u postgres psql\n\\password postgres\n\\q\n\n```\n\n## Access PostgreSQL\n\n### Access PostgreSQL Shell (psql):\n\n```sh\nsudo -u postgres psql\n```\n\n### Basic Commands\n> Once in psql, you can execute SQL commands. Here are a few essential commands:\n\n- \\l: List all databases.\n- \\c database_name: Connect to a specific database.\n- \\dt: List all tables in the current database.\n- \\q: Quit psql.\n\n## Configure PostgreSQL for Use with Applications\n\n### Edit PostgreSQL Configuration (if necessary):\n\n> Modify PostgreSQL configuration files (postgresql.conf and pg_hba.conf) located typically in /etc/postgresql/<version>/main/ to adjust settings like authentication methods, listen addresses, etc.\n\n### Connect PostgreSQL with Django or Other Applications\n> Update your application's database settings (settings.py for Django) to use PostgreSQL with the appropriate credentials (USER, PASSWORD, HOST, PORT).\n\n## Remove PostgreSQL\n\n### Stop\n> If PostgreSQL is running, stop the service:\n\n```sh\nsudo service postgresql stop\n```\n\n### Remove\n> Remove PostgreSQL and its configuration files:\n```sh\nsudo apt-get remove --purge postgresql\\*\n```\n\n### Clean up\n> Remove any remaining configuration files:\n\n```sh\nsudo rm -r /etc/postgresql/\nsudo rm -r /etc/postgresql-common/\nsudo rm -r /var/lib/postgresql/\n\n\n\n```\n\n### Additional Tips\n\n- Backup and Restore: Use tools like pg_dump and pg_restore for database backups and restoration.\n- Security: Ensure PostgreSQL is configured securely, especially if accessible from outside WSL.\n"},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":false,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"jupyter"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env